<paragraph blockId="25.[151,1437,968,2038]" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">
Notes. This species appears to be closely related to 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb" authorityYear="2016" box="[772,1180,1832,1858]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Signoretia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="266" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mishmiensis">
<emphasis box="[772,937,1832,1858]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">S. mishmiensis</emphasis>
Viraktamath &amp; Webb
</taxonomicName>
described from 
<collectingCountry name="Myanmar" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">Myanmar</collectingCountry>
but also known from southern 
<collectingCountry box="[560,627,1868,1894]" name="China" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">China</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[644,745,1868,1894]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
; Dietrich unpublished), which is nearly identical in external appearance and has similar male terminalia, including basally crossed aedeagal processes. The new species is easily distinguished by the presence of large spines on male abdominal segment X, a preapical ventral spine on the aedeagal shaft, and the hairlike microtrichia of the basal aedeagal processes restricted to a small area near the apex (
<figureCitation box="[160,250,2012,2038]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="26.[151,250,785,809]" captionTargetBox="[207,1376,183,761]" captionTargetId="figure-26@26.[206,1382,181,761]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="FIGURE 9. Signoretiinae. Signoretia tamdaoensis sp. n., male holotype. A–B, lateral and dorsal habitus; C, genital capsule, lateral view; D, pygofer and base of anal tube, lateral view; E, subgenital plate, ventral view; F–G, genitalia, ventral and lateral views; H, aedeagus apex, posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4424112" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4424112/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="266">Fig. 9G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
